{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617699"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:15:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:15:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16486"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16486"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.04,0.92,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9177"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68690"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9177"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16486"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54147"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5073"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21784"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22632"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68690"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EInhaled anticholinergic medications (such as ipratropium) are commonly prescribed for patients with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease to improve their respiratory symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of inhaled anticholinergics?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits inflammatory mediator release from mast cells","Blocks beta-2 adrenergic receptors","Blocks muscarinic receptors on airway smooth muscle","Reduces mucus production in submucosal glands","Stimulates beta-2 adrenergic receptors"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EInhaled anticholinergics primarily work by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking muscarinic receptors on airway smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E. This antagonism prevents acetylcholine-mediated bronchoconstriction, leading to bronchodilation. Common examples include ipratropium and tiotropium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits inflammatory mediator release from mast cells\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of mast cell stabilisers such as sodium cromoglicate, which act to prevent the release of inflammatory substances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks beta-2 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E would cause bronchoconstriction and worsen respiratory symptoms, which is contrary to the therapeutic goal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces mucus production in submucosal glands\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; while anticholinergics may have a minor effect on mucus secretion, this is not their primary therapeutic mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates beta-2 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of beta-2 agonists such as salbutamol, which are a different class of bronchodilators.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe advantage of inhaled delivery is that it allows direct action on airway receptors while minimising systemic absorption and side effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inhaled anticholinergics block muscarinic receptors in airway smooth muscle, reducing bronchoconstriction.","Ipratropium and tiotropium are inhaled anticholinergics used in chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.","Anticholinergics have minimal systemic absorption when inhaled, reducing side effects."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54147"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16486"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54147"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T10:20:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T10:21:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9177"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68690"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Lev